This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fight against the growing machist trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
One professor noted that most students at the best university in the world can't take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of the kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
At the end, a student approached me and said, \"Why do you tell me this only in the last year?\"
She claimed that no one had ever talked to her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,\" he told The Telegraph.
Dispensed for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of university health services, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee, curtains, basketballs, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical benefits and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
\"We know that this will not change students' behaviour instantly.
However, we believe they have the right to know this information - in the same way that you have the right to know the effects of smoking on health,\" added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride of \"a white night\" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students make sleeplessness a growing problem.
Having adequate sleep and good quality should be the \"secret weapon\" of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain in a way of inanitation, making them hungry permanently.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian chemistry and physical biology student, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and moved him to insist that he be offered to the entire campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to propose to all third-cycle students to follow a similar study program before joining the well-known institution.
