The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highlands area seeks to reveal how bats use landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will guide future conservation activities.
The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
Professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of shouts of bats and the activities of the different species.
A map and a habitat report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the largest areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of grasslands and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, the populations of bats have declined considerably during the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that affect the paths and result in the loss of their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can the paper kill-mouths and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as the attacks of company cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, given their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to identify insects and obstacles to their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes the bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, brush inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization has also established the first and only reserve of Scottish bats on the Treave site in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of Scotland's ten species of bats.
David Thompson, the domain manager, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
\"Here, in Three, we have an ideal place for bats,\" he says.
\"We have old buildings, many old trees and all good habitat.
But there is still much to learn about bats, so much so that the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to prosper.\"
He stressed the importance of verifying the presence of bats prior to the maintenance of the properties, because by destroying without wanting it a single nest of maternity, it could cause the death of 400 females and small ones, or even the disappearance of a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, to disturb them, or to destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to assist.
She said, \"We still have a lot to learn about our bats and about many of our species, we don't know what's going on in their populations right now.\"
