Point of information on the red tide: Low concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The last report of the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the county areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - which causes fear of declining concentrations.
The red tide covers approximately 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in less sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or beyond the county of Pinellas were reported last week, low to high concentrations across the county of Hillsborough, higher concentrations in the county of Manatee, higher concentrations at the bottom of the county of Sarasota or off, mean concentrations in the county of Charlotte and low concentrations in the county of Lee and off of the county of Manatee, high concentrations at the bottom or wide in the county of Collier.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation was reported in the northwest of Florida during the past week.
